.\" Manpage for quicsd
.\" groff -man -Tascii quicsd.1 | less
.TH QUICSD 1 "April 2026" "QUICS v0.2" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
quicsd \- QUIC server for secure file transfer and remote command execution
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B quicsd
[\fI\-c\fR \fICONFIG_FILE\fR]
[\fI\-\-version\fR]
.br
.B quicsd create\-ca
[\fI\-u\fR \fIUSERID\fR]
[\fI\-\-name\fR \fINAME\fR]
[\fI\-\-email\fR \fIEMAIL\fR]
[\fI\-\-password\fR \fIPASSWORD\fR]
.br
.B quicsd create\-cert
[\fI\-u\fR \fIUSERID\fR]
[\fI\-\-name\fR \fINAME\fR]
[\fI\-\-surname\fR \fISURNAME\fR]
[\fI\-\-email\fR \fIEMAIL\fR]
[\fI\-\-password\fR \fIPASSWORD\fR]
[\fI\-\-ca\-password\fR \fIPASSWORD\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B quicsd
is a server that provides secure file transfer and remote command execution
over the QUIC protocol with mutual TLS authentication. It uses X.509 client
certificates for user identification and provides isolated home directories
for each user.
.PP
The server implements user isolation where each non-root user gets a home
directory at \fIstorage.root_dir\fR/\fIuserid\fR (created
automatically with 0700 permissions). The root user has access to the
entire storage root directory.
Paths are resolved relative to user home directories for isolation.
.PP
The server includes built-in certificate management commands to create a
Certificate Authority (CA) and user certificates using ECDSA P-256 cryptography.
Client certificate validation is mandatory; the server will not start without
a valid CA certificate specified in the configuration.
.SH CRYPTOGRAPHY
The server uses a hardened TLS 1.3 configuration with post-quantum
hybrid cryptography:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Preferred key exchange: X25519MLKEM768 (X25519 + ML-KEM-768 hybrid)
.IP \(bu 2
Fallback curves: X25519, CurveP256
.IP \(bu 2
Cipher suites: TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384,
TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256, TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256
.IP \(bu 2
TLS 1.3 only with mutual authentication
.IP \(bu 2
Forward secrecy enabled by default
.RE
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-c\fR, \fB\-\-config\fR \fICONFIG_FILE\fR
Path to configuration file (default: ./config/server.yaml)
.TP
\fB\-\-version\fR
Print version information and exit
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B create\-ca
Create a new ECDSA P-256 Certificate Authority.
.RS
.TP
\fB\-u\fR, \fB\-\-userid\fR \fIUSERID\fR
CA user ID (used for filename, default: ca)
.TP
\fB\-\-name\fR \fINAME\fR
CA common name (default: QUICS CA)
.TP
\fB\-\-email\fR \fIEMAIL\fR
CA email address (optional)
.TP
\fB\-\-password\fR \fIPASSWORD\fR
Password for CA PKCS#12 file (optional, but recommended)
.RE
.TP
.B create\-cert
Create a new user certificate signed by the CA.
.RS
.TP
\fB\-u\fR, \fB\-\-userid\fR \fIUSERID\fR
User ID (required, used for filename)
.TP
\fB\-\-name\fR \fINAME\fR
User's first name (optional)
.TP
\fB\-\-surname\fR \fISURNAME\fR
User's last name (optional)
.TP
\fB\-\-email\fR \fIEMAIL\fR
User's email address (optional)
.TP
\fB\-\-password\fR \fIPASSWORD\fR
Password for the user PKCS#12 file (optional, but recommended)
.TP
\fB\-\-ca\-password\fR \fIPASSWORD\fR
Password for the CA PKCS#12 file (required if CA was created with \-\-password)
.RE
.SH CONFIGURATION
The server reads configuration from a YAML file. The following options are
available:
.TP
.B listen_addr
IP address to listen on (default: "0.0.0.0")
.TP
.B listen_port
Port to listen on (default: 4243)
.TP
.B tls.cert_file
Path to server TLS certificate (PEM format)
.TP
.B tls.key_file
Path to server private key (PEM format, must have 600 permissions)
.TP
.B auth.client_ca_file
Path to CA certificate for client certificate validation (mandatory).
The server will not start if this field is empty.
.TP
.B auth.certs_dir
Directory where CA and user certificates are stored (default: ./certs).
.TP
.B storage.root_dir
Root directory for file storage
.TP
.B quic.max_idle_timeout_seconds
Maximum idle timeout in seconds (default: 300, 0 = default 120s)
.TP
.B quic.keep_alive_period_seconds
Keep-alive period in seconds (default: 15, -1 = disable, 0 = default 15s)
.TP
.B shell.enabled
Enable remote command execution (default: true)
.TP
.B shell.allowed_commands
List of allowed command patterns (regex or literal strings)
.TP
.B shell.max_execution_time_seconds
Maximum command execution time in seconds (default: 30)
.TP
.B shell.allowed_env_vars
List of allowed environment variable names
.TP
.B log.type
Log destination: "stderr", "file", or "syslog" (default: "stderr")
.TP
.B log.file_path
Path to log file (required if log.type = "file")
.TP
.B log.syslog_host
Syslog host (currently only local syslog supported, leave empty)
.TP
.B log.syslog_port
Syslog port (default: 514, ignored for local syslog)
.SH USER IDENTIFICATION
User IDs are extracted from client X.509 certificates:
.IP \(bu 2
The UID field (OID 0.9.2342.19200300.100.1.1) is extracted from the
certificate Subject
.IP \(bu 2
If the UID field is not present, the CommonName is used as fallback
.IP \(bu 2
User "root" gets direct access to the storage root directory
.IP \(bu 2
Other users get home directories at \fIstorage.root_dir\fR/\fIuserid\fR
.SH CERTIFICATE GENERATION
Certificates can be generated using the built-in commands or external scripts.
.TP
.B Built-in commands
Use \fBquicsd create\-ca\fR to create a new ECDSA P-256 Certificate Authority
and \fBquicsd create\-cert\fR to create user certificates signed by the CA.
Certificates are saved in the \fIauth.certs_dir\fR directory.
.TP
.B External scripts
The \fIcerts/\fR directory contains OpenSSL scripts for certificate generation:
.RS
.TP
.B regenerate-certs.sh
Regenerate CA, server, and client certificates with proper Subject Alternative
Names (SANs) for localhost and 127.0.0.1
.TP
.B generate-user-cert.sh
Generate user certificates with UID, email, and name fields
.RE
.SH EXAMPLE CONFIGURATION
.nf
listen_addr: "0.0.0.0"
listen_port: 4243

tls:
  cert_file: "certs/server.crt"
  key_file: "certs/server.key"

auth:
  client_ca_file: "certs/ca.crt"
  certs_dir: "./certs"

storage:
  root_dir: "./files"

quic:
  max_idle_timeout_seconds: 300
  keep_alive_period_seconds: 15

shell:
  enabled: true
  allowed_commands: ["^ls.*", "^rm.*", "cat", "echo", "pwd", "^cd.*"]
  max_execution_time_seconds: 30
  allowed_env_vars: ["PATH", "HOME", "USER"]

log:
  type: "stderr"
.fi
.SH STARTING THE SERVER
.nf
# With default configuration
quicsd

# With custom configuration
quicsd -c /etc/quics/server.yaml

# Check version
quicsd --version

# Create a new CA
quicsd create-ca --userid ca --name "QUICS CA" --email admin@example.com

# Create a user certificate
quicsd create-cert --userid alice --name Alice --surname Smith --email alice@example.com
.fi
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.quicsc/
Default client certificate directory
.TP
.B certs/
Certificate generation scripts and test certificates
.TP
.B config/server.yaml
Default configuration file
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR quicsc (1)
